# Clean Mileage, Engine and Power
#Remove string values from Mileage, Engine, Power
def clean_str(myval):
    if isinstance(myval, str):
        result =(myval.replace('km/kg', '').replace('kmpl','').replace('bhp','').replace('null','').replace('CC','')).strip()
        if result.strip() == '':
            return np.nan
        else:
            return float(result)
    else:
        return np.nan

    
#Clean mileage column, remove strings and convert to float
df['Mileage'] = df['Mileage'].apply(clean_str)
    

#Clean Engine column, remove strings and convert to float
df['Engine'] = df['Engine'].apply(clean_str)
    
#Clean Power column, remove strings and convert to float
df['Power'] = df['Power'].apply(clean_str)
df.reset_index()

#Function to remove Lakh and Cr from New Price and convert Cr to Lakh, by multiplying Cr by 100.
def new_price_to_num(new_price_val):
    """This function takes in a string new price, conforms data to Lakh and returns a float"""
    if isinstance(new_price_val, str):  # checks if `new_pric_val` is a string
        if new_price_val.find('Cr') > -1:
            return float(new_price_val.replace('Cr','')) * 100
        else:
            return float(new_price_val.replace('Lakh','')) 
    else:  
        return np.nan
                     
df['New_Price'] = df['New_Price'].apply(new_price_to_num)

  • Max data value looks very off. Its highly unlikely someone drove 6.5 million kilometers in the same car.
  • Median is 52618 Kilometers while mean is 58318 Kilometers. It appears that the outliers are skewing the mean significantly.
  • I will replace anything greater than the 98th quantile with the 90th quantile.
In [26]:
#copy dataset
df_no_outliers = df.copy()
In [27]:
#get rid of anything larger than 98%
def assign_quant98(myval):
    quant98 = np.quantile(df_no_outliers["Kilometers_Driven"], [.98])
    if myval > quant98:
        return np.quantile(df_no_outliers["Kilometers_Driven"], [.90])
    else:
        return myval

df_no_outliers['Kilometers_Driven'] = df_no_outliers['Kilometers_Driven'].apply(assign_quant98)

# function to compute adjusted R-squared
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# function to compute MAPE
def mape_score(targets, predictions):
    return np.mean(np.abs(targets - predictions) / targets) * 100


# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE
    mape = mape_score(target, pred)  # to compute MAPE

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Conclusion¶

  • The best performing excludes the New_Price column and retains highly correlated columns. It has an RMSE score of .337 and an R-squared score of 88%.
  • The business should focus on Diesel and Petrol cars as nearly all sales reflect these two Fuel Types.
  • To maximize advertising dollars, the business should focus on Hyderabad and Mumbai as they represent about 25% of the business. Additional they may want to focus on Kochi, Pune, and Caimbatore because combined with Mumbai and Hederabad, these 5 cities represent 57% of the business.
  • The business should focus on Manual vehicle sales as they represent 71% of the business.
